d":"Shebbear, Devon, England","Orchard Portman, Somerset, England":"Orchard Portman, Somerset, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"Somerset, England"},"nl":{"1380–24 December 1419":"1380–24 december 1419","1378–1440":"1378–1440","1380–1419":"1380–1419","1380–1440":"1380–1440","1407–1472":"1407–1472","1412–1420":"1412–1420","1346–1410":"1346–1410","1358–1420":"1358–1420","1440":"1440","1472":"1472","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","24 December 1419":"24 december 1419","1358":"1358","1412":"1412","1346":"1346","1378":"1378","1399":"1399","1410":"1410","1420":"1420","before 29 November 1407":"vóór 29 november 1407","1419":"1419","1407":"1407","Shebbear, Devon, England":"Shebbear, Devon, England","Orchard Portman, Somerset, England":"Orchard Portman, Somerset, England","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"Somerset, England"},"en":{"1380–24 December 1419":"1380–24 December 1419","1378–1440":"1378–1440","1380–1419":"1380–1419","1380–1440":"1380–1440","1407–1472":"1407–1472","1412–1420":"1412–1420","1346–1410":"1346–1410","1358–1420":"1358–1420","1440":"1440","1472":"1472","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","24 December 1419":"24 December 1419","1358":"1358","1412":"1412","1346":"1346","1378":"1378","1399":"1399","1410":"1410","1420":"1420","before 29 November 1407":"before 29 November 1407","1419":"1419","1407":"1407","Shebbear, Devon, England":"Shebbear, Devon, England","Orchard Portman, Somerset, England":"Orchard Portman, Somerset, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"Somerset, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Orchard","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["topographic or occupational name from residence near (or perhaps employment at) an orchard, Middle English <i>orchard</i> (Old English <i>ortgeard</i>, <i>orceard</i>).","habitational name from any of the places called Orchard. Those in Devon and Somerset are named from Old English <i>ortgeard</i>, <i>orceard</i> (a compound of <i>wort</i>, <i>wyrt</i> ‘plant’ (later associated with Latin <i>hortus</i> ‘garden’) + <i>geard</i> ‘yard, enclosure’), while East and West Orchard near Shaftesbury in Dorset derive from Primitive Welsh <i>ar</i> ‘beside, in front of, facing’ + <i>ced</i> ‘wood’.","rare variant of Scottish   Urquhart  . Compare   Orahood  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Urquhart","meanings":["Scottish (Ross and Cromarty): habitational name from any of various places in Scotland so called, notably the barony of Urquhart (Inverness), or places in Ross and Cromarty, Morayshire, and Fife. All are thought to derive from Pictish <i>ar</i> ‘on, by’ + Pictish <i>carden</i> ‘enclosure’ or ‘wood, copse’. Some bearers of this name trace their descent from William <i>de Urchard</i>, who fought for Robert the Bruce between 1297 and 1328."]},{"name":"Orahood","meanings":["Probably an altered form of   Orchard   3, itself a rare English variant of Scottish   Urquhart  .","History: The Orahoods can trace their origin to Alexander, Joshua, and Thomas Orahood, who in the second half of the 18th century lived in VA and are believed to come to America from Scotland. Their surname is also listed in the forms <i>Orrahud</i>, <i>Arahood</i>, <i>Arrowhood</i>, and <i>Orchard</i>, the last one being the most likely original form."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":2,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When William Orchard was born in 1380, in Orchard Portman, Somerset, England, his father, Robert de Orchard, was 34 and his mother, Margaret Manningford, was 22. He married Alice Trevett in 1399, in Orchard Portman, Somerset, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died on 24 December 1419, in his hometown, at the age of 39."},"et":{"1380–24 December 1419":"1380–24. detsember 1419","1378–1440":"1378–1440","1380–1419":"1380–1419","1380–1440":"1380–1440","1407–1472":"1407–1472","1412–1420":"1412–1420","1346–1410":"1346–1410","1358–1420":"1358–1420","1440":"1440","1472":"1472","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","24 December 1419":"24. detsember 1419","1358":"1358","1412":"1412","1346":"1346","1378":"1378","1399":"1399","1410":"1410","1420":"1420","before 29 November 1407":"enne 29. novembrit 1407","1419":"1419","1407":"1407","Shebbear, Devon, England":"Shebbear, Devon, England","Orchard Portman, Somerset, England":"Orchard Portman, Somerset, England","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"Somerset, England"},"fi":{"1380–24 December 1419":"1380–24. joulukuuta 1419","1378–1440":"1378–1440","1380–1419":"1380–1419","1380–1440":"1380–1440","1407–1472":"1407–1472","1412–1420":"1412–1420","1346–1410":"1346–1410","1358–1420":"1358–1420","1440":"1